    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-01-27T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-01-27T14:00:00-05:00" n="507"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d507">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94112/310: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-01-27T14:00:00-05:00"
                            >January 27, 1940—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>43. Your 70, January 24, 6 p.m., opening of Yangtze. In reply to inquiry of the
                    Inspector General of the Chinese Maritime Customs, please inform him that this
                    Government has consistently objected to any interference with the rights of
                    Americans with respect to navigation and trade on the Yangtze and naturally
                    desires to see normal navigation on the Yangtze restored; that this Government
                    is likewise, as it has repeatedly indicated, interested in the maintenance of
                    the administrative integrity of the Chinese Maritime Customs; but that this
                    Government is not inclined at this moment to attempt to influence the Chinese
                    Government in its attitude in the matter under consideration.</p>
                <p>Sent to Shanghai. Repeated to Chungking and Peiping. Peiping please send cipher
                    text to Tokyo by air mail.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
